{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516440"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:42:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:42:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12625"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12625"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.06,0.13,0.02,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5110"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52393"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5110"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12625"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37742"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8549"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14510"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15183"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52393"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 87-year-old woman is admitted with a fractured neck of femur after a fall at home. Her medical history includes Alzheimer\u0027s dementia, atrial fibrillation, insomnia, gout, congestive heart failure, and hypertension. Her regular medications include allopurinol, buprenorphine patch, citalopram, digoxin, furosemide, melatonin, oxazepam, paracetamol, perindopril-indapamide, risperidone 0.5 mg, rivaroxaban , rosuvastatin, spironolactone and zopiclone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurgical internal fixation of the fracture is performed successfully, and she is making a good recovery until the third post-operative day when she has multiple episodes of confusion and verbal aggression towards her nurse. Conservative measures such as verbal redirection, maximising natural light, visitation from a family member, confirming the function of her hearing aids, and nursing support were all unsuccessful in reducing her verbal aggression. A septic screen was performed what demonstrated a normal haemaglobin, normal white cell count, normal platelet level and a CRP  of 9 (normal \u0026lt;10). Blood and urine culture results are pending however her urinalysis was negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn review, she is confused and shouting at the staff. Her blood pressure is 132/93 mmHg, pulse 103/min, temperature 37.0\u00b0C, and SpO2 98% on room air. Her BMI is 26 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Her pain score has been 0. She has no notable petechial rashes, no increased work of breathing, or jaundice. She has passed wind, her catheter is patent, and she has been producing an appropriate amount of urine. Blood glucose is recorded at 6.5 mmol/L. After verbal de-escalation, she is more stable but appears anxious and apprehensive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next course of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Order EUC bloods and review medications","Investigate for a neck of femur (NOF) induced fat embolism syndrome","Once off haloperidol 2.5 mg IM","Subcutaneous morphine","Increase regular oral risperidone to 1 mg"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of post-operative, hyperactive delirium on a background of long-standing behavioural and psychological symptoms of dementia. The most appropriate first step is to consider environmental controls such as lighting, visual aids such as working clocks, and verbal redirection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere should also be an appropriate investigation of potentially reversible reasons for delirium, which can be remembered by the mnemonic \u201cDelirium\u0022 (Image). Some risk factors post-surgically for delirium include uncontrolled pain, urinary retention, bowel obstruction, and infections. These are less likely given the negative septic screen, 0 pain scale, passing stool, and functioning urinary catheter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the medications the patient is on, including the combination of an ACE inhibitor, loop diuretic, and potassium-sparing diuretic, there is a risk of metabolic or electrolyte derangement, which includes hyponatraemia, which can itself cause confusion. In addition, hyponatraemia can commonly occur in elderly patients post-operatively due to SIADH and should always be considered in delirium. Polypharmacy is a major contributor to post-operative delirium and therefore the role of benzodiazepines, zopiclone, risperidone, digoxin and buprenorphine (high risk medications in elderly patients) should be reviewed. As such, \u003Cstrong\u003Emedication review and EUC bloods\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, \u003Cstrong\u003Esubcutaneous morphine\u003C/strong\u003E would not be necessary as her pain score is 0.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is a risk of \u003Cstrong\u003Efat embolism syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E post-surgery on long bone surgery as lipids enter the bloodstream. However, Gurd\u2019s major criteria state this would likely present with respiratory insufficiency, cerebral involvement, and petechial rash (from thrombocytopenia), which, besides confusion, are absent in the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe role of antipsychotic medications such as \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Erisperidone\u003C/strong\u003E in delirium is controversial. It would be more appropriate to focus on reversible causes of delirium before utilising such medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Where possible, use other measures before using chemical restraint in cases of delirium","When prescribing medications for the elderly, \u0027go low and go slow\u0027."],"references":["Marcantonio ER. Delirium in Hospitalized Older Adults. N Engl J Med 2017;377:1456-66. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMcp1605501","Jin Z, Hu J, Ma D. Postoperative delirium: perioperative assessment, risk reduction, and management. Br J Anaesth. 2020 Oct;125(4):492-504. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32798069/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37742"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12625"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20699"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20699"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/S69U3hGemeScQb0E9bzvERTAR4qAHv.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/S69U3hGemeScQb0E9bzvERTAR4qAHv.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":543,"height":428}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37742"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-04T17:56:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-04T17:57:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5110"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52393"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id"